04905nam a22007215i 9780691210254DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20202009nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912102547 a10.1515/97806912102542doi  a(DE-B1597)546354  a(OCoLC)1159418727  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPR151.I53bF57 2009eb 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a820.9/3529972231 aFlint, Kate, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Transatlantic Indian, 1776-1930 /cKate Flint. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b40 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tChapter One. Figuring America -- tChapter Two. The Romantic Indian -- tChapter Three. "Brought to the Zenith of Civilization": Indians in England in the 1840s -- tChapter Four. Sentiment and Anger: British Women Writers and Native Americans -- tChapter Five. Is the Indian an American? -- tChapter Six. Savagery and Nationalism: Native Americans and Popular Fiction -- tChapter Seven. Indians and the Politics of Gender -- tChapter Eight. Indians and Missionaries -- tChapter Nine. Buffalo Bill's Wild West and English Identity -- tChapter Ten. Indian Frontiers -- tConclusion. Indians, Modernity, and History -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book takes a fascinating look at the iconic figure of the Native American in the British cultural imagination from the Revolutionary War to the early twentieth century, and examining how Native Americans regarded the British, as well as how they challenged their own cultural image in Britain during this period. Kate Flint shows how the image of the Indian was used in English literature and culture for a host of ideological purposes, and she reveals its crucial role as symbol, cultural myth, and stereotype that helped to define British identity and its attitude toward the colonial world.Through close readings of writers such as Charles Dickens, Elizabeth Gaskell, and D. H. Lawrence, Flint traces how the figure of the Indian was received, represented, and transformed in British fiction and poetry, travelogues, sketches, and journalism, as well as theater, paintings, and cinema. She describes the experiences of the Ojibwa and Ioway who toured Britain with George Catlin in the 1840s; the testimonies of the Indians in Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show; and the performances and polemics of the Iroquois poet Pauline Johnson in London. Flint explores transatlantic conceptions of race, the role of gender in writings by and about Indians, and the complex political and economic relationships between Britain and America.The Transatlantic Indian, 1776-1930 argues that native perspectives are essential to our understanding of transatlantic relations in this period and the development of transnational modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aAmerican literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexAmerican influences. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aGroup identity in literature. 0aIndians in literature. 0aIndiansxTransatlantic influences. 0aIndigenous peoples in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691210254zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691210254423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691210254.jpg  a978-3-11-066258-0  PUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKA